E. COLI EHEC - ISRAEL (02): (HADAROM) FIRST REPORT, KIBBUTZ NURSERY, PETTING ZOO SUSPECTED
******************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 4 May 2016
From: Jacob Moran-Gilad <jacob.moran-gilad@moh.gov.il> [edited]


Israel, VTEC [verotoxin-producing _E. coli_] outbreak, Southern District [HaDarom]
----------------------------------------------------------------------
An outbreak of gastroenteritis has been reported to affect a nursery in the Nir-Oz Kibbutz in Southern Israel. Of 14 infants, a total of 7 (50 percent) have developed symptoms ranging from diarrhea to bloody diarrhea or fever. 3 out of the 7 cases (aged 4-10 months) have developed hemolytic-uremic syndrome (HUS) and 2 of them required intensive care. A total of 5 infants have been admitted to the regional hospital (Soroka Medical Center) for treatment of this infection.

A local petting farm has been suggested as a potential source of infection and was closed for visitors by the district health authorities until further notice. This, as well as other possible sources are currently being investigated.

Infection control measures implemented include closure of the nursery, heightened awareness and specimen referral for new diarrhea cases, and maintenance of strict personal, food, and environmental hygiene.

VTEC [also known as enterohemorrhagic _E. coli_, EHEC], is an uncommon cause of gastrointestinal infection in Israel, with only a handful of cases reported annually. However, it is a well documented cause of bloody diarrhea and HUS worldwide.

To the best of our knowledge this represents the 1st documented outbreak of VTEC infection in Israel.

--
Jacob Moran-Gilad
<jacob.moran-gilad@moh.gov.il>
